  "summary": "<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/27/a-pulitzer-winner-wrote-a-short-story-without-using-the-letter-i.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"A Pulitzer winner wrote a short story without using the letter &quot;I&quot;\"><img alt=\"First pages of Carol Shields short story &quot;Absence&quot;\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"961\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/no-i.jpg?fit=1200%2C961&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1200\" /></a><p>In 1969, French author Georges Perec wrote <em>La Disparition</em>, an entire novel that does not contain the letter E. In 1994, Gilbert Adair translated it into English as <em><a href=\"https://amzn.to/4bAAIng\">A Void</a></em> — also without a single E. I've only read portions of it, and I'm still amazed that someone could tell a coherent story without the most common letter in the English language. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://boingboing.net/",
